erations \u00f7 net profit) over the last 5 years.","why_useful":"Profit you can't collect as cash is fragile; >0.8\u00d7 means earnings are real cash, <0.6\u00d7 is an accrual red flag.","why_it_can_fail":"One-off working-capital swings or a capex year can distort a single ratio; the 5-yr median smooths it."},{"label":"Balance-sheet safety","value":0.24,"unit":"\u00d7 D/E","status":"good","read":"Conservatively financed (D/E 0.24\u00d7, interest cover 4.5\u00d7).","meaning":"Latest debt-to-equity and interest coverage (EBIT \u00f7 interest) from the balance sheet.","why_useful":"Low debt and high interest cover let a business survive a downturn; high debt amplifies trouble.","why_it_can_fail":"Off-balance-sheet leases/guarantees aren't captured; a cash-rich firm can show low D/E yet still be risky elsewhere."},{"label":"Earnings momentum","value":3.23,"unit":"% YoY","status":"ok","read":"Profit up 3% YoY \u2014 modest.","meaning":"Trailing-twelve-month net profit vs the year-ago TTM (and whether the YoY rate is rising = 'accelerating').","why_useful":"Improving, accelerating earnings tend to drive re-rating; falling profit warns of a deteriorating business.","why_it_can_fail":"TTM can be lumpy for cyclicals/one-offs; cross-check the multi-year trend on the Fundamentals tab."}]},"valuation":{"ok":true,"is_bank":false,"pe_now":13.2,"pe_percentile":18.0,"median_pe":16.2,"earnings_yield_pct":7.58,"pb":1.69,"ev_ebitda":11.49,"quality_score":71.0,"pat_cagr_5y_pct":30.4,"peg":0.43,"cheapness":{"status":"good","read":"P/E at the 18-percentile of its 10-yr range \u2014 cheap vs its own history."},"expectations":"At 13.2\u00d7 earnings for ~30% 5-yr profit CAGR, the market is paying \u22480.43\u00d7 growth (PEG). >2 = a lot already priced in; <1 = cheap if growth holds. This PEG divides TTM P/E by TRAILING 5-year annual PAT CAGR (endpoint-to-endpoint) \u2014 a time-axis mismatch vs the textbook FORWARD-EPS PEG, and one abnormal base/terminal year distorts the CAGR. A rough t